If Ovechkin catches Gretzkys goal record, will he be the best?

Overview

Most of us lived through the Washington Capitals season that ended in winning the Stanley Cup in 2018. Their leader for that championship run and for the past decade is Alexander Ovechkin, their prolific offensive powerhouse and flashy goal scorer. Other teams are aware what a strong weapon Ovechkin can be know for his big hits, skating speed and frequent goals. But with all this flash and success, Ovechkin is not the all time NHL leading goal scorer. That title belongs to Wayne Gretzky, The Great One, who played during the 1990s and 2000s. Many call him the greatest player of all time because of his scoring but also his all around solid play. Gretzky has 894 goals and Ovechkin is trying to catch him but time is running out for the 36 year-old Ovechkin. Will he catch up to Gretzkys magic goal scoring number and if he does how will he be compared the The Great One and the rest of the leagues current and former stars.

This race for the all-time scorer title is all-over the sports media. If you want to read to study more about it click on the link here.



This project includes the following activities

  • Calculate using standard math computation if Ovechkin can catch Gretzky
  • Compare Ovechkin to Gretzky and the leading players
  • Build a model that predicts the Ovechkins goals scored

Calculate Projected Data for Goals and Points

First we need to calculate who in the NHL can catch Gretzkys total career goals. I decided to do this using relatively simple method:

  • Determine how many more seasons each play may play using 40 years old as the retirement age
  • Calculate estimated goals to be scored in the future by multiplying the years remaining by 70 games played per season by each players average goals per game
  • Add estimated goals to current goals scored and that will give the projected goals at the end of each players career

There are weaknesses in this simplification including

  • A player may not play until they are 40
  • A player may not score at the same rate as they age
  • A player may not play only or at least 70 games per season

There is an interesting data point that was noticed during my research Gretzky scored more goals per game when he was in his 20s but Ovechkin scored more goals per game in his 30s. Does this mean that he can keep up.


Explanation for calculations are in code comments.

Exploratory Data Analysis Ovechkin vs Gretzky

First lets describe what each header item means:

  • Season: Year player played hocket
  • Team: Players team
  • GP Games played: Total games played per season
  • G Goals: Goals scored per season
  • PTS Points: Points scored per season, point = goals + assists
  • SOG Shots on Goal: Total shots on goal per season
  • % Shooting Percent: Goals divided by shots on goal, goal = shot
  • GWG Game Winning Goals: Goals scored by player that won the game for players team
  • GWP Game Winning Points: Pointts scored by player that won the game for players team

Now lets perform linear regression on both Ovechkins and Gretzkys goals to see if correlation between goals and games played. The reason this is important is that Ovechkin is 36 so he has a limited number of games left in his career, so this correlation is important.

Linear Regression Analysis of Ovechkin and Gretzky Data

These two graphs show the regression analysis of Ovi and Wayne. In the analysis the R2 values are around 0.3-0.4. The R squared value measures how closely the regression models the data. It usually ranges from 0-100%, and the higher the value, the better the model fits the data. Although 30-40% may seem low, these linear regressions are relatively accurate as we are trying to fit a model to human behavior. R-squared values for human behavior usually are around 40%. Looking at the results, the coefficient of games played for Ovi is 0.5703 and for Wayne it was 0.9051. According to this model, based solely on the coefficient of games played (the coefficient of games played is the slope of the line), Wayne is still the best player as the trend for goals scored per games played is still higher than Ovis. However, when comparing the linear regression graphs, overall, Ovi plays more games and scores more often than Wayne. If Wayne played more games, then according to this regression he would have scored more than Ovi. But since Ovi played more games, he scored more. From this we can gather that the rate at which Wayne scores per game is higher, but Ovi plays and scores more often.


I found an interesting article about the R-squared values and what low values and high values represent based on the data. You can read it here.

Lets Try to Find If Statistics Really Impact Goals

Although some of the graphs show some linear correlation, I want to keep searching for a statistical analysis that may show this more clearly. There has been much debate for years about what hockey stats really matter in terms of naming the greatest player or most prolific goal scorer. Currently, tthe trend in all sports is saturation of data analysis and identification of trends from this analysis to better coach teams and select players. Recently NHL data analysts have been narrowing their focus to shots, not necessarily goals. The reason is that the variation in shooting percentage of star players is not significant. In fact there have been many data science papers written on the debate relationship between shots, goals, and the best players. So here is some analysis of the relationship between shots and goals. Why is the shots the most significant measure in a players performance. Well, hockey experts say that it is because shooting percentage (goals made per shots taken) variation is small among all players. Therefore, the best chance to increase the players goals made is to increase the shots taken. If you are interested in understanding more about this discussion on NHL goals, click here.

Predicting Goals with Machine Learning

If you know even the slightest information about hockey you will know that scoring goals can happen for many reasons skill of the player, luck of the puck being tipped, and goals caused by pulling the goalie at the end of the game. So trying to predict goals can be very difficult. If fact the experts have created sophisticated prediction models that use parameters that create an expected goals data point for every play in every game. For this project, I will make two attempts at the model. Both using two variable linear regression, but with different variables to see if the prediction and model accuracy is better when comparing models.

Conclusion: So Will Ovechkin Catch Gretzky?

The goal of this project was to try to determine if Alex Ovechkin can catch Wayne Gretzky to become the highest goal scorer in NHL history. At the beginning of the project I used simple math with goals per game assumptions to determine that he could catch Wayne Gretzky after 4 seasons. I analyzed the plots of games played for the Top 200 stars, then specifically for Ovechkin and Gretzky. These were analyzed using linear regression and although their R-squared values are low they still are in the range for typical human related results using linear regression. Then I tried to find additional data correlations that could help is predicting Ovechkins career goals. I plot shots, game winning shots, points, game winning point, and playing time all in an effort to look for correlation. Well research shows that is difficult to find statistics that predict goals scored. Even so, I ran machine learning regression models and found the results for goals predicted were less than the original simple math. My research on hockey statistics shows that arguably shots of goal is the best predictor to goals but if we could predict that for the rest of Ovechkins career then that would be too simple. Even though the models predicted less goals than necessary to catch Gretzky, I think Ovechkin really will become the NHL career goals leader by the time he retires.
